Loading data

setwd("/Users/JakeWong/Documents/Classes/Fall 2016/STA 141A/Project/student-alcohol-consumption")
d1 = read.csv("student-mat.csv")
d1 = d1[,-c(31:32)] #dropped G1 and G2
Use forward and backward selection to find important variables as our initial model.

fit = lm(G3~.,d1) step = stepAIC(fit, direction="both") step$anova # display results

The model we will be working with is as following
\begin{eqnarray} G3 =\beta_0 + \beta_{sex} + \beta_{age} + \beta_{famsize} + \beta_{Medu} + \beta_{Mjob} + \beta_{studytime} + \beta_{failures} + \beta_{schoolsup} + \beta_{famsup} + \beta_{romantic} + \beta_{freetime} + \beta_{goout} + \beta_{absences} + \beta_{Dalc} + \beta_{Walc} \end{eqnarray}

NOTE:

  • Dropped age since the range is small and there are outliers, which might be the reason why the stepwise model thinks this is significant.
  • Add in alcohol consumption, because it's what we'd like to study.
    • Then let's fit the model and the summary is as following:

II. Relationship between variables and effect on G3

2.1. Going out and Alcohol Consumption (weekend and weekday)

In [83]:
out_dalc <- ggplot(d2, aes(Dalc, colour=factor(goout))) + geom_density(adjust=2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1) +
  ggtitle("PDF of Weekday Alcohol") + labs(x = "Weekday Alcohol Consumption") #plot pdf of weekday alcohol,factor by goout
out_dalc
dalc_walc <- ggplot(d2, aes(Walc, colour=factor(goout))) + geom_density(adjust=2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1) +
  ggtitle("PDF of Weekend Alcohol") + labs(x = "Weekend Alcohol Consumption")  #plot pdf of weekend alcohol,factor by goout
dalc_walc

As for weekend alcohol consumption, students who reported a lower frequency of going out are more likely to consume less alcohol on the weekend and as the level of alcohol consumed on the weekend increases we see that students are more likely to have answered that they go out a lot. 

As for weekday alcohol consumption, we see that people on are less likely across the board to report high rates of drinking during the week. Although the trends are slighter and more skewed towards less drinking than the weekend alcohol consumption we see that students that report going out more are still more likely to report drinking more during the week and students that report going out less are more likely to report drinking less during the week.

These two PDFs indicate that we would expect to see peoples alcohol consumption preferences at least somewhat mirrored by their preferences in frequency going out/being social and so looking at the effect of reported rates of going out on final grades we should see those implications as a potential partial indicator of the effect of alcohol consumption on final grades.
Another interesting PDF that challenges popular belief is shown when we compare weekend alcohol consumption against final grades:
In [84]:
walc_g3 <- ggplot(d2, aes(G3, colour=factor(Walc))) + geom_density(adjust=2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5) +
  ggtitle("PDF of Final Grade and Weekend Alcohol") + labs(x = "Final Grade")
walc_g3

Here we challenge the conventional wisdom that student alcohol consumption is negatively related to students final grades. We see that in this data set there is not a major difference between any of the different levels of weekend alcohol consumption and expected final grade with all the levels of alcohol consumption from low to high most likely to receive a relatively average grade in the class. After seeing this it is possible that time spent socializing is more important than whether or not that extracurricular activity involves the consumption of alcohol or not.

2.2. Genders, Relationship status and Study Time

In [86]:
sex_study <- ggplot(d2, aes(studytime, colour=factor(sex))) + geom_density(adjust=2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1) +
  ggtitle("PDF of Gender and Study Time") + labs(x = "Study Time")
sex_study

    When breaking down amount of time spent studying reported by students we see that female students are expected to on average study more than male students. This means that any effects from study time on final grade are going to be experienced more by female students than male students.
In [88]:
ggplot(d2, aes(x=Romantic, y=G3, fill=Gender)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(title="Boxplotbetween Gender and Romantic Relationship")

Then, we break down how students final grades look when separated by relationship status across gender: we see that out of a relationship students have a similar mean across gender. However, Its notable that that female students have both a lower mean and a wider spread of final grades than male students. For female students in relationships, their final grades lower quartile decreases to around 7 while the upper quartile stays about the same as the one for female students who arent in a relationship.

2.3. Failures

In [89]:
ggplot(d2, aes(failures)) + ggtitle("Grade by Failures") + geom_histogram(aes(fill=factor(G3)),binwidth=1, position="fill")

This shows that if students have never failed a class before, then they have a relatively even distribution of probability to receive grades all across the spectrum. However, if a student has failed 3 classes, they are given basically no chance of receiving a final grade of 20 in this math class. And failing one or two classes give decreasingly likely chances of receiving a very high final grade in the class. This graph essentially indicates that if you have failed a class before you are less likely to do well in this class.

2.4. Family and School educational support

The following graphs show the PDFs of students separated by whether or not they are receiving family or school support in their class:

In [91]:
ggplot(d2, aes(G3, fill = factor(famsup), colour = factor(famsup))) + geom_density(alpha = 0.1) 
ggplot(d2, aes(G3, fill=factor(schoolsup), colour = factor(schoolsup))) + geom_density(alpha = 0.1)

In both the above graphs we see that students who are receiving support whether it be from the school or from family are given higher probabilities of receiving lower final grades in the class. This is likely due to selection bias because students receiving support are likely to be students who are not doing as well in the class and therefore be more in need of support. So we cannot interpret this as support is correlated with students performing worse, as it is possible that these students receiving support are doing better in the class than they would be without support even if its still not as good as the students who are doing well in the class without any support. It is also important to notice that since we have no reported values for grades 1-3 as noted earlier in the report the dip in both graphs there is not reflective of the effect of support or lack of it.

2.5. Absences

Next we examined the effect of student absences on final grade. A histogram shows that the number of reported absences to have the highest frequency at zero and skewed rather hard with most of the values being below 10 out of 93.

In [96]:
abs_bar <- ggplot(d2,aes(x= Gender,y = absences,group = Gender)) + geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Gender)) +
  facet_wrap(~cut(G3,4))
abs_bar

Above is a hex bin representation of absences clustered as they relate to final grade where we see no clear relationship and a large cluster at 0 absences and a final grade of 0 in the class. We believe this is an irregularity in the data set potentially related to the missing values of 1-3 in G3. To further break down absences relationship with final grade we box plotted absences by quartile of final grades. We found that it was hard to determine anything with the lowest quartile being so weighed down by all the values of zero absences and zero as a final grade in the class.

2.6 Family Size

In [97]:
ggplot(d2, aes(G3)) + ggtitle("Grade by Family Size") + geom_density(aes(fill=factor(famsize)), position="fill")

The lower end of the graph appears to be slightly disrupted by the lack of values 1-3 but the focus on this graph is on the right side where we see that students receiving a 20 as a final grade in the class are more likely to be of a family sized less than three. It is tempting to think that these kids are only children and so are receiving more attention around there studies from their parents. It is possible by definition of the variable though that a family of size less than three or equal to three is a single parent with two kids in which case time and resource allocation would be very different than an only child with two parents. This makes the findings of this graph inconclusive and hard to draw real relationships from.

2.7. Parental Education and Jobs

Students final grades are the dependent variable and from the final graph, mothers educations seemed to be the most significant variable as it is the root node. If the mother did not receive an education past secondary school, then the students fathers job is the next deterministic factor. Jobs in the health sector and categorized as other are the most impactful ones compared to the other recorded ones like civil services and teacher. From this point, fathers who work in the health field produce more children From here, the fathers education is the least impactful factor for determining student final grades. Interestingly, if the students mother did attend secondary school or college, the next deterministic factor is the mothers job, not fathers job or education. In fact, it seems the more educated the mother is, the less important the fathers background is which is supported from the step regression as fathers education was a less significant variable on final grades than mothers education. Students with highest grades recorded have mothers with higher education and whose backgrounds are teachers. Most of the students from this sample however, have mothers who have lower than a secondary education. Their final grades are also lower than those with more educated mothers. Fathers education levels do not seem as impactful because final scores seem similar.

III.Conclusion

We analyze a group of 395 students final scores in math as an indication of student performance and use their backgrounds to determine significant relationships and possible prediction variables. The distribution were working with has a mode at 10 and is not roughly normal as expected because of missing values from 1 to 4. There are however, enough observations to perform observations through graphs like histograms, boxplots, and correlelograms and tests like the stepwise selection and tree modeling. 

We tested notable relationships between weekend and daily alcohol consumption and saw overall, those who consumed more alcohol over the weekend also consumed more alcohol during the weekdays. Going out also is proportional to alcohol assumption. When analyzing alcohol consumption over the weekend and final grades, the pdfs are distributed roughly normal for all factors, including those who score higher scores of 3, 4, and 5 suggesting alcohol consumption doesnt negatively affect grades. Those with factors 1 and 2 are slightly skewed to the right so more densities of people score better but there is no huge significance between the distributions between all these factors. Since going out is proportional to alcohol consumption, socializing also does not seem to negatively affect grades. 

According to gender, females tend to study more on average but are more likely to be negatively affected by romantic relationships because females mean final grades decrease while males mean final grades stay about the same when in a relationship. The spread of females scores also widens but overall, they decrease with this widening range. Failures in classes decrease students chances of receiving high scores. In terms of family life, mothers education is the most significant variable in determining whether students perform well or not and students with more educated mothers tend to receive higher scores. Most students, however, enter school with mothers who do not have an education past secondary school and they perform average so mothers education may positively affect their childrens scores but not negatively affect them. We are unable to conclude anything concrete for final grades, students receiving financial support and absences, and family size as there are many other possible explanations and unaccounted variables.
